{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643107"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:49:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:49:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17984"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17984"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.88,0,0.12,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79180"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10698"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64532"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8539"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24913"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79180"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cells initiates inflammation of the liver in non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Microglia","Kupffer cells","Splenic macrophages","Clara cells","Raglow cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENon-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) is characterised by inflammation and damage due to fat accumulation in the liver, not related to alcohol consumption. \u003Cstrong\u003EKupffer cells\u003C/strong\u003E are the resident macrophages of the liver and play a crucial role in initiating and perpetuating inflammation in NASH. They are activated in response to various stimuli, including free fatty acids and inflammatory cytokines, leading to the release of pro-inflammatory mediators that contribute to liver damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroglia\u003C/strong\u003E are the resident macrophages of the central nervous system and are not involved in liver inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplenic macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E are involved in immune responses in the spleen and do not play a direct role in liver inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClara cells\u003C/strong\u003E are found in the respiratory tract and are not involved in liver pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaglow cells\u003C/strong\u003E do not exist.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Kupffer cells are liver macrophages that play a key role in initiating inflammation in non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH).","Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis is characterised by liver inflammation and damage due to fat accumulation, not related to alcohol consumption.","Understanding the role of liver-specific immune cells is crucial in the pathogenesis of liver diseases like NASH."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64532"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17984"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64532"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T16:29:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T16:29:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10698"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79180"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"